{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13858"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13858"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.28,0.45,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49034"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6475"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13858"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49034"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents to the surgical outpatient clinic with a large, painless abdominal swelling that has been gradually increasing in size over the past year. He has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus and a surgical history of a laparotomy for small bowel adhesiolysis five years ago. His regular medications include hydrochlorothiazide, olmesartan and metformin. He is a non-smoker. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a large midline protrusion, which is more pronounced when he coughs or leans forward (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent surgical repair","Elective laparoscopic repair","Weight loss program","Abdominal binder","Watchful waiting"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a large midline incisional hernia, which is a well recognised complication following abdominal surgery, particularly in overweight individuals. In this elderly patient with comorbidities, the most appropriate initial management is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight loss program\u003C/strong\u003E. Weight loss can reduce the size of the hernia, decrease intra-abdominal pressure, and improve overall surgical risk if an operation is eventually required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case as the patient is asymptomatic and there are no signs of incarceration or strangulation. The risks of emergency surgery in an elderly patient with comorbidities outweigh the potential benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective laparoscopic repair\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially beneficial in some cases, is not the first-line management for this patient. The large size of the hernia and the patient\u0027s age increase the risk of surgical complications. Non-operative management should be attempted first. If surgery is to be undertaken, it would be an open approach and not laparoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal binder\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some symptomatic relief but does not address the underlying issue and is not a definitive management strategy. It may be considered as an adjunct to conservative management if the patient experiences discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWatchful waiting\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not the most appropriate initial management. While it may be a reasonable approach for some patients, active intervention through weight loss offers the potential to improve the patient\u0027s condition and reduce risks associated with the hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHernia surgery, especially for large or complex hernias, is becoming increasingly specialised, with hernia MDT\u0027s and surgical societies being created. The importance of prehabilitation, surgical planning and tailoring surgical options for specific patients is being recognised more and more.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Weight loss is the initial management for patients with large incisional hernias, especially in older patients with comorbidities.","Incisional hernias are a common complication following abdominal surgery, particularly in the midline.","Conservative management is often preferred for large incisional hernias in elderly patients due to the high risk of surgical complications."],"references":["Turner R. A GP primer on incisional hernia. Australial Journal of General Practice. 2018;47(9):621-624. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/d08c5067-57bb-46d3-825c-ec8534e9d971/A-GP-primer-on-incisional-hernia.aspx","de Jong D, Wegdam J, Berkvens E, et al. The influence of a multidisciplinary team meeting and prehabilitation on complex abdominal wall hernia repair outcomes. Hernia. 2023;27(3):609-616. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36787034/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13858"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20805"},{"type":"media","id":"20806"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20805"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3FhM8vXez3X0wFLUqcz3VVCXQnaEBM.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3FhM8vXez3X0wFLUqcz3VVCXQnaEBM.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"media","id":"20806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20806"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/r0YCcrHTeuWeOJQGIw6Uw0ToIzzxpZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/r0YCcrHTeuWeOJQGIw6Uw0ToIzzxpZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T16:18:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T12:38:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6475"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49034"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou